<paragraph id="8BC53698FFABFFA3E999100EFBFE5210" blockId="43.[756,1140,1040,1064]" box="[756,1140,1040,1064]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">
<heading id="D08D81F4FFABFFA3E999100EFBFE5210" box="[756,1140,1040,1064]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" reason="2">
Family 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFABFFA3E82B100EFBFE5210" authority="Gray, 1821" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1821" box="[838,1140,1040,1064]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Vespertilionidae Gray, 1821</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC53698FFABFFA3E9B1105AFB81534A" blockId="43.[684,1213,1092,1394]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFABFFA3E9B1105AFC075264" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1821" box="[732,909,1092,1116]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Vespertilionidae</taxonomicName>
is the most speciose family in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFABFFA3E9A41078FCCB5246" authorityName="Blumenbach" authorityYear="1779" box="[713,833,1126,1150]" class="Mammalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Chiroptera</taxonomicName>
, with a nearly cosmopolitan distribution except in the Arctic and 
<collectingCountry id="F36D7608FFABFFA3EF611097FBF55299" box="[1036,1151,1161,1185]" name="Antarctica" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
. Vespertilionids are characterized by the reduction of the second digit of the wing to the metacarpal and a single small phalanx and the presence of a long tail, reaching the edge of the uropatagium (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFABFFA3EF1A110BFCAB5368" author="Koopman, K. F." pageId="43" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 217" refId="ref37895" refString="Koopman, K. F. 1994. Chiroptera: systematics. Handbuch der Zoologie VIII (Mammalia) 60: 1 - 217." type="journal article" year="1994">Koopman, 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Two species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFABFFA3E8B81126FB975377" authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1829" box="[981,1053,1336,1359]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFABFFA3E8B81126FB975377" box="[981,1053,1336,1359]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recorded in one locality during our study.
</paragraph>
